Edinburgh 2013: Nikolai Lugansky's love and toil for Rachmaninov
Ahead of concertos at the Edinburgh Festival next week, Russian pianist Nikolai Lugansky tells John Allison why he just can't get enough of Rachmaninov. Range: Nikolai Lugansky represents the gold standard in Rachmaninov interpretation. By John Allison
7:30AM BST 17 Aug 2013
Comments
"If you are in love with somebody, it’s quite difficult to explain why.” The pianist Nikolai Lugansky is speaking of Rachmaninov, whose music has defined his career thus far. But this is no unrequited love, for of this generation of pianists – the self-effacing Muscovite is 41 – Lugansky represents the gold standard in Rachmaninov interpretation. His recent, award-winning recording of the two Rachmaninov sonatas (on the Naïve label) encompasses all the contrasts between the works and makes one of the strongest cases on disc for the neglected and fiendishly challenging First Sonata. With a Proms appearance in Rachmaninov’s Third Concerto just behind him and the composer dominating his three concerts at the Edinburgh Festival, it’s easy to forget that Lugansky is in fact a completely rounded musician. As a warm-up for his two Rachmaninov concertos with the Russian National Orchestra next week, his Edinburgh recital on Thursday was balanced with Schubert, Liszt, Wagner and Janácek. “For me, Janácek wrote the most emotional music ever. He is so intense you need a holiday after playing his works.”
